<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-810-204  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 810 204.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  Sept 1990 v7 n9 p50(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Transforming DOS applications to Unix. (includes related articleson Hunter Systems and Ashton-Tate)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Campbell, Art.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The companies that help microcomputer software run on Unix supporteither DOS-to-Unix porting or translation.andP;  Porting is expensiveand time consuming, but popular.andP;  Translation, a faster and easiermethod that converts Intel-based microcomputer software to largeplatforms through the use of computer-aided software engineering,is not supported by many DOS publishers.andP;  The only company thathas translation products is Hunter Systems (Mountain View, CA).andO;Ashton Tate has chosen to use porting because porting allows thecompany more control over its products.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hunter Systems Software Inc. (product development)Ashton-Tate (product development).andO;Topic:     UNIXMS-DOSApplicationsSoftware PublishersSoftware MigrationProduct DevelopmentComputer-Aided Software Engineering.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>